ed. I'm noticing the file has staged and unstaged changes, so maybe I'm looking at different versions of the code. Let me focus on the actual bug: the API returns git commits in the history field, but the frontend should be fetching prompt content instead. I need to check if the `prompt-content` endpoint is being called correctly when a prompt entry is expanded.\n\nBuilding the event listener...\n\nI'm constructing the HTML for each prompt file with a details element that includes a data-file attribute, then adding a loading message inside. When toggled, it should fetch the file content via the prompt-content endpoint. The handler sets the response as plain text and reads from disk, so that part should work—but I'm wondering if the issue is that the endpoint is returning an error or 404 instead of the actual file content.\n\nLet me think through this differently. The initial render only shows \"Loading...\" in the prompt-content div, so the git commits must be coming from somewhere else. Either the fetch is somehow pulling data from the wrong endpoint, or there's another piece of code rendering those commits. I'm checking the handler logic again—it definitely reads the file with os.ReadFile and doesn't execute any git commands. Maybe the URL routing is getting confused and the prompt-content request is hitting the project-info handler instead?\n\nActually, wait. Looking at the URLs more carefully, they're distinct endpoints, so that's probably not it. Let me reconsider whether the initial loadProjectInfo is actually rendering the commit history inside the details element. I'm looking at the code that builds the HTML for the prompt files...\n\nBuilding the details element...\n\nThe code only uses the file path and puts a loading placeholder inside. The history data from the API response is never touched by the frontend, so there's no way git commits would appear unless the prompt-content endpoint itself is returning that data somehow.\n\nLet me trace through the route handlers to see if there's any route matching issue. In Go 1.22+, the routes should be distinct, but I'm wondering if the `/api/projects/{name}/info` pattern might be catching requests meant for the more specific `/api/projects/{name}/info/prompt-content` endpoint.\n\nActually, that shouldn't happen with exact pattern matching. Let me shift focus—when the user clicks expand, they see \"git commits\" instead of the expected content. Maybe the issue isn't with routing at all, but with what the JavaScript is actually loading or how the response is being handled.\n\nWriting the JavaScript function... I'm wondering if the toggle event listener isn't firing at all, or if there's another piece of code somewhere else that's actually rendering the history. After reviewing the entire template though, I don't see any other rendering logic for the prompt history. Let me reconsider the bug description more carefully—maybe \"Prompts section\" refers to something in the workflow step drawer rather than the project info panel, since clicking a step shows prompt config values as file paths. I need to check how the drawer handles this.\n\nActually, wait—the template file shows both staged and unstaged changes, which means there could be modifications I haven't seen yet that either caused the bug or are attempting to fix it. Let me look at the git diff to understand what actually changed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22892,"cache_read_input_tokens":15181,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":22892},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ca6cf770-913c-44a9-bb21-f3642b81e32c","uuid":"0784803e-e00d-423c-af7a-6e8c027193fc"}
